ption": "When clouds get too full of water droplets, they release the water back to Earth as rain, snow, sleet, or hail. This is called precipitation."}, {"step": 4, "name": "Collection", "description": "The water that falls back to Earth collects in oceans, lakes, rivers, or soaks into the ground to become groundwater, ready to start the cycle again."}], "corePrinciples": [{"name": "Water is Always Moving", "description": "Water on Earth is never still; it's constantly traveling through the sky, land, and oceans in a continuous loop."}, {"name": "Water is Recycled", "description": "The Water Cycle shows us that Earth has a limited amount of water, but it's always being cleaned and reused, so we don't run out."}, {"name": "The Sun Powers the Cycle", "description": "The Sun's energy is essential because it provides the heat needed to lift water into the atmosphere, starting the whole process."}], "relevantVocabulary": ["Evaporation", "Condensation", "Precipitation", "Collection", "Transpiration", "Runoff", "Groundwater", "Atmosphere"]}